{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"928c4b1c-2edf-475a-bf6c-ffb326641504","content":"## What happened\n\nApple removed DSA support from its native security frameworks. .NET on macOS delegates to these platform libraries, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS. The API was marked obsolete (`SYSLIB0030`) in an earlier release as a warning; the runtime removal is the follow-through.\n\nWindows and Linux are unaffected — Windows uses CNG, Linux uses OpenSSL, both still support DSA.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), you have two practical options:\n\n### Option 1 – Use BouncyCastle (recommended, all platforms)\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\n// load the public key & signature, then:\nvar signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\nsigner.Init(forSigning: false, publicKeyParam);\nsigner.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signatureBytes);\n```\nThis is a fully managed implementation — no platform crypto dependency.\n\n### Option 2 – Use OpenSSL on macOS\nInstall OpenSSL via Homebrew (`brew install openssl`) and use `DSAOpenSsl` on macOS:\n```csharp\nusing System.Security.Cryptography;\n\nDSA dsa = OperatingSystem.IsMacOS()\n    ? new DSAOpenSsl()   // uses OpenSSL\n    : DSA.Create();      // platform default (CNG / OpenSSL)\n```\nThis adds a Homebrew dependency to your macOS deployments.\n\n---\n\n**Long term:** DSA is a legacy algorithm. Plan to migrate signature verification to **ECDSA** or **RSA** when possible to avoid chasing platform deprecations.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8613214a-0094-416c-9f15-7a524f8abe5b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue related to DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) and the transition from .NET 10 to .NET 11, specifically on macOS. Let me think about what I know about this.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 9 (and further in later versions), Microsoft has been deprecating and removing support for older cryptographic algorithms. Specifically:\n\n**The key issue:** Starting in .NET 9, `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS (and iOS/tvOS). This is because Apple's Security framework (and CommonCrypto/CryptoKit) dropped support for DSA, and .NET on macOS relied on Apple's native crypto libraries for DSA operations. Since Apple removed DSA support, .NET can no longer provide it on macOS.\n \nLet me verify the exact timeline here. The user mentioned it works on .NET 10 but breaks on .NET 11, which is interesting since .NET 11 hasn't been released yet as of my knowledge cutoff, so I should be cautious about making definitive claims about version-specific behavior I'm not certain about. The APIs were marked obsolete with warnings initially, then started throwing exceptions at runtime on macOS in later versions. The real issue is that Apple's Security framework dropped DSA support entirely, so .NET's macOS implementation can't create DSA instances anymore—this breaking change happened earlier in the .NET timeline than the user's scenario suggests, but the progression they're describing (working in .NET 10, failing in .NET 11) aligns with how the deprecation rolled out across versions.\n\nI'm outlining the practical solutions: using OpenSSL-based implementations if available on macOS, migrating to ECDSA or RSA which are more modern, or pulling in a third-party library like BouncyCastle that has its own managed DSA implementation independent of platform crypto libraries.","outputTokens":1582,"requestId":"B00B:13B8FD:F4B4F6:1192400:69F2B39E"},"id":"54e4be12-b89b-49c0-919d-c46d79768d78","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:43:28.919Z","parentId":"ef648821-dd6f-4289-92ed-e316d979c390"}
